\begin_layout Standard
This section presents a Schumpeterian model based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abramsPatentValueCitations2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, featuring growth through creative destruction by entrants, as well as
 the possibility for incumbent monopolist of researching a defensive technology
 that increases research costs for entrants.
 I first present a single-sector model to clarify the mechanism at play
 within each sector in the economy and study a constant-growth equilibrium
 analytically.
 I then extend the model to two sectors, and I consider a fixed supply of
 inventors, which shuts down within-sector misallocation occurring independently
 of inventors' movements across sectors.
 I show that increasing markups in one of the sectors of the economy lead
 to a misallocation of inventors towards defensive innovation in the less
 competitive sector.
 Finally, I study the optimal allocation of R&D subsidies needed to achieve
 maximum growth in a calibration of the two-sector model that matches moments
 of the R&D distribution in 1997.
 Proofs are reported in Appendix 
