While this assumption is not necessary for the results to hold, it simplifies
 the analysis considerably.
 In the following section, I will consider both production and research
 labor as given by a fixed endowment in the constant growth equilibrium
 of the economy.
 In that case, the assumption is equivalent to assuming that both labor
 endowments grow at a constant rate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The representative household owns a differentiated portfolio of all the
 firms in the economy, with rate of return 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

, and receives a wages 
\begin_inset Formula $w,w^{RD},$
\end_inset

 for each unit of production and research labor, respectively.
 I assume that the economy is closed and that the final good is only used
 for consumption, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}=Y_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This structure yields a standard Euler equation and R&D labor supply with
 Frisch elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
