\begin_layout Standard
The market structure in the model follows 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "acemogluIntellectualPropertyRights2012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "abramsPatentValueCitations2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Accordingly, the consumption good in the economy, which I take as numeraire,
 is the unit-measure aggregate of products
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln Y_{t}=\int_{0}^{1}\ln y_{t}(i)\mathrm{d}i.\label{eq:Y}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The market for each product 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}(i)$
\end_inset

 consists of an incumbent and a fringe of competitors.
 In what follows, I focus on a single market, dropping the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Each firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in the sector produces an undifferentiated good with the linear production
 technology:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{j,t}y_{j,t}=l_{j,t},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,t}$
\end_inset

 denotes the labor requirement to produce a unit of output, and 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{j,t}$
\end_inset

 the production labor employed by the firm.
 Competitors have labor requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{e,t}=c_{t}$
\end_inset

, while the incumbent faces a lower unit labor requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{I,t}=\frac{c_{t}}{\phi}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi>1$
\end_inset

.
 Profit maximization by the incumbent gives an optimum limit price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}=w_{t}c_{e,t}$
\end_inset

, which leads her to capture the entire market and act as a monopolist,
 charging a markup 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi>1$
\end_inset

 on the marginal cost.
 The Cobb-Douglas assumption on the final good implies equilibrium normalized
 profits,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pi_{t}}{Y_{t}}\equiv\pi=\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right).
\]

\end_inset


