In a previous version of this paper, I prove that a sufficient condition
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,\omega}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 to increase with markups is that the research intensity of incumbents is
 more elastic than entrants', a condition which is verified in all the numerical
 simulations I explored.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 As the following proposition shows, higher markups unambiguously increase
 research efforts by incumbents and entrants, as well as the share of R&D
 labor accruing to incumbents.
 
\end_layout

